me":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Watton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of <b>Watten</b>, from the Middle English personal name <i>Wat</i>, a pet form of   Walter   (see   Watt  ), with the characteristically West Midland genitival suffix <i>-en</i>.","habitational name from Watton (East Yorkshire), or perhaps in some cases from Watton (Norfolk), Watton at Stone (Hertfordshire), or Wattons in Bere Ferrers (Devon). The Yorkshire placename derives from Old English <i>wēt</i> ‘wet’, later replaced by Old Norse <i>vátr</i> ‘wet’, + Old English <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’. The Norfolk and Devon placenames probably derive from the Old English personal name <i>Wada</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i>. The Hertfordshire placename probably derives from Old English <i>wād</i> ‘woad’ + <i>tūn</i>.","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Walter","meanings":["English (of Norman origin), German, Dutch, Polish, Swedish, and Danish: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This personal name was introduced into England both in the reign of Edward the Confessor and by the Normans (in the forms <i>Walt(i)er</i>, <i>Waut(i)er</i>). After the Norman Conquest it soon became one of the most popular personal names in Britain. Compare   Walther  .","Germanized or Americanized form of Czech, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian <b>Valter</b> and Czech <b>Valtr</b>: from the personal name <i>Valter</i>, <i>Valtr</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"Mathilda","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Old German: Mighty battle maid"],"variants":[{"name":"Maud","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."]},{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mathilda De Watton was born in 1146, in Watton, Yorkshire, England. She married William De Routh in 1161, in Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1201, in Yorkshire, England, at the age of 55."},"et":{"Cir 1146–1201":"1146–1201","1139–1197":"1139–1197","1164–Male":"1164–Surnud","1217–1268":"1217–1268","1146–1201":"1146–1201","1217":"1217","1139":"1139","1268":"1268","1201":"1201","1146":"1146","Cir 1146":"1146","1164":"1164","1197":"1197","1161":"1161","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Watton, Yorkshire, England":"Watton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Cir 1146–1201":"1146–1201","1139–1197":"1139–1197","1164–Male":"1164–Kuollut","1217–1268":"1217–1268","1146–1201":"1146–1201","1217":"1217","1139":"1139","1268":"1268","1201":"1201","1146":"1146","Cir 1146":"1146","1164":"1164","1197":"1197","1161":"1161","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Watton, Yorkshire, England":"Watton, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Cir 1146–1201":"1146–1201","1139–1197":"1139–1197","1164–Male":"1164–Décédé","1217–1268":"1217–1268","1146–1201":"1146–1201","1217":"1217","1139":"1139","1268":"1268","1201":"1201","1146":"1146","Cir 1146":"1146","1164":"1164","1197":"1197","1161":"1161","Yorkshire, England":"Everwyck, Angleterre","Watton, Yorkshire, England":"Watton, Everwyck, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Mathilda De Watton est née en 1146, à Watton, Everwyck, Angleterre. Elle a épousé William De Routh en 1161, à Everwyck, Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 2 fils. Elle est décédée en 1201, à Everwyck, Angleterre, à l’âge de 55 ans."},"de":{"Cir 1146–1201":"1146–1201","1139–1197":"1139–1197","1164–Male":"1164–Verstorben","1217–1268":"1217–1268","1146–1201":"1146–1201","1217":"1217","1139":"1139","1268":"1268","1201":"1201","1146":"1146","Cir 1146":"1146","1164":"1164","1197":"1197","1161":"1161","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Watto